Project: Insurance Policy Cancellation¶

This dataset comes from the 2022 NESS Statathon (Theme 1) from 2022.¶

Challenge: Using historical policy data, create a multiclass predictive model to predict the policies that are most likely to be canceled and those most likely to be renewed, as well as understand what variables are most influential in causing a policy cancellation.¶

Dataset Description¶

The Kangaroo data set is based on 4 years of property insurance policies from 2013 to 2017. There are roughly 1 million policies in the training data and each policy only has one observation. There were almost 230,000 policies canceled during the effective term.

Variable descriptions

  • id - Policy id (cannot be used in model)
  • tenure - Number of years with Kangaroo
  • claim.ind - Occurrence of claim (0=no, 1=yes)
  • n.adults - Number of adults in the property
  • n.children - Number of children in the property
  • ni.gender - Gender of policyholder
  • ni.marital.status - Marital status of policyholder (0=no, 1=yes)
  • premium - Price of the policy
  • sales.channel - Medium through which policy was purchased
  • coverage.type - Type of coverage
  • dwelling.type - Type of dwelling
  • len.at.res - Length at residence (how long policyholder lived at property)
  • credit - Financial credit level of policyholder
  • house.color - Color of house
  • ni.age - Age of policholder
  • year - Year of the policy
  • zip.code - Zip code of the property
  • cancel - cancelation indicator (0=not cancel, 1=may cancel but can be convinced, 2=cancel).

#This list contains the features that we want to impute with the mean. These are mostly continuous variables.
continous_features = ['zip.code', 'ni.age', 'premium', 'n.children', 'tenure']
for col in X_train:
  if col in continous_features:
    # imputing continuous features with a mean of the column
    X_train[col] = X_train[col].fillna(X_train[col].mean())
  else :
    # imputing categorical features with a mode of the column
    X_train[col] = X_train[col].fillna(X_train[col].mode()[0])

merged_df = pd.merge(X_train, y_train, left_index=True, right_index=True)

# Define the label names and color codes for the legend
legend_labels = {0: 'Not Canceled', 1: 'May Cancel', 2: 'Canceled'}
legend_colors = {0: 'blue', 1: 'orange', 2: 'green'}

# Plot the line plot with Seaborn
ax = sns.lineplot(
    x="year", 
    y="premium",
    data=merged_df,
    palette='bright',
    hue='cancel',
    legend='brief'
)

# Get the handles and labels of the current legend
handles, labels = ax.get_legend_handles_labels()

# Create a new legend with custom labels and colors
new_handles = [handles[i] for i in range(len(handles))]
new_labels = [legend_labels[int(label)] for label in labels]
new_colors = [legend_colors[int(label)] for label in labels]
ax.legend(new_handles, new_labels, loc='center left',bbox_to_anchor=(1, 0.5))

# Show the plot
plt.show()

Observations¶

  1. Policies with premium rates above 900 have a "not cancelled" status and this status has remained unchanged from 2013 to 2016.
  2. Policies with the premium in range [895-897] have a status of "may cancel but can be convinced". This status has shown an increasing trend with premiums yearly till 2015, after which there is a gradual decrease from 2015 to 2016.
  3. The "canceled" status has remained consistent throughout the years and is maintained at a premium rate range of 896-898.

so, we can say that policies with higher premiums are less likely to be cancelled.

Plot-2¶

In [26]:
# create a list of categorical columns
cat_cols = ['house.color', 'credit', 'coverage.type', 'dwelling.type', 'sales.channel', 'ni.gender']
# create a figure with multiple subplots
fig, axs = plt.subplots(nrows=3, ncols=2, figsize=(12, 18))

# loop through the subplots and plot the data
for i, ax in enumerate(axs.flat):
    if i < 6:
        col = cat_cols[i]
        sns.countplot(x=col, hue='cancel', data=merged_df, ax=ax)
        ax.set_title(f'Plot for {col}')
        ax.set_xlabel('')
        ax.set_ylabel('Count')
        # add percentage labels on top of each bar
        for p in ax.patches:
            height = p.get_height()
            ax.text(p.get_x() + p.get_width() / 2., height + 1, '{:.1f}%'.format(height / len(merged_df) * 100), ha="center")
        ax.legend(title="cancel", labels=["Not cancel", "May Cancel", "Cancel"], loc='best', borderaxespad=0.)

# adjust the spacing between subplots
fig.tight_layout()

# show the plot
plt.show()

Observations¶

  1. House color: The ratio between each pair in ['Cancel', 'May Cancel', 'Not Cancel'] remains more or less the same. This ratio indicates non deterministic decision of cancellation based on house color.
  2. Credit: Customers with high credit score have a high ratio(~5) of Not cancel:cancel which indicated low probability of cancelling. On the other hand this trend is poosed by customers with low credit score where the ratio is low(~1.3).
  3. Coverage type: Customers with coverage type C have the highest cancellation rate, which is higher than the cancellation rate for customers with coverage type B and higher than the cancellation rate for customers with coverage type A. The ratio of "not cancel" to "cancel" for coverage type A is high (3.3), which means that coverage type A has a low cancellation rate. So, companies can do market research to find out why coverage C has a high rate of cancellation or push coverage type A to lower the cancellation rate even more in the future.
  4. Dwelling type: Customers who own houses (as opposed to tenants or condo owners) have the highest cancellation rate, which is almost 2 times the cancellation rate for condo owners, and almost 2.5 times the cancellation rate for tenants.
  5. Sales channel: Customers who purchase insurance through brokers have the highest cancellation rate, which is almost 1.5 times the cancellation rate for customers who purchase insurance through phone, and almost 4 times the cancellation rate for customers who purchase insurance online.
  6. Gender: Both male and female customers have similar cancellation rates, with a slightly higher cancellation rate for males (11.4%) compared to females (10.5%).

Overall, credit scores, dwelling, coverage type and sales channel affects the cancellation rate

Observations¶

  1. Observing correlations of variables with cancel(target variable), the highest absolute correlation is with ni.age. cancel and ni.age have a -0.1 correlation which means that increasing age reduces the number of cancellations.
  2. Two of the most significant correlations are [tenure, age] and [n.children, ni.marital.status] which state the obvious facts that increasing age increases tenure and marital status has a direct positive correlation with the number of children.

# feature importance

result = permutation_importance(RFC, X_test, y_test, n_repeats=5, random_state=42)
perm_sorted_idx = result.importances_mean.argsort()

tree_importance_sorted_idx = np.argsort(RFC.feature_importances_)
tree_indices = np.arange(0, len(RFC.feature_importances_)) + 0.5

fig, ax1 = plt.subplots(1, 1, figsize=(6, 4))
ax1.boxplot(result.importances[perm_sorted_idx].T, vert=False,
            labels=X_sampled.columns[perm_sorted_idx])
fig.suptitle('RFC Feature Importance', y=1.05)
fig.tight_layout()
plt.show()

These are the top 5 Features that we found using permutation_importance

  1. credit
  2. sales.channel
  3. zip.code
  4. year
  5. ni.age

Business Recommendations and Observations¶

  1. We see that people with less credit have a high chance of cancelling the subscription as compared to the people with high credit scores. Taking this into consideration, we should advertise the products to people with higher credit scores via targeted ads and marketing campaigns. Also, we should investigate further into what is causing low credit customers to cancel their subscription.
  1. We can observe that the more tenure a person has, less likely they cancel the subscription. To improve the number of consumers for the products, we should implement schemes to retain customers for a longer time. A good step in that direction would be to collect regular feedbacks about products and a discourse on how to improve the user experience.
  1. Another observation we have is that younger customers tend to cancel more than the older customers. May be the products and marketing campaigns aren't as relavant to the younger audience and should be geared towards the younger population and also keeping the elder customers happy.
  1. Customers aquired through broker are less likely to cancel the subscription than customers through other mediums. We should incentivize broker and encourage them to get more customers. Also, increasing the number of brokers can help us achieve lower cancellation and higher retention.
  1. The PDP Graph relationship between Zipcode and cancel, we can observe that the line variesin the range of 0 and 0.30, which likely indicates that there is a weak relationship between zip codes and the likelihood of cancellation.
